     1→\documentclass[11pt]{article}
     2→
     3→\usepackage[utf8]{inputenc}
     4→\usepackage[T1]{fontenc}
     5→\usepackage{amsmath,amsthm,amssymb,amsfonts}
     6→\usepackage{mathtools}
     7→\usepackage{graphicx}
     8→\usepackage[margin=1in]{geometry}
     9→\usepackage{hyperref}
    10→\usepackage{cleveref}
    11→\usepackage{enumitem}
    12→\usepackage{tikz}
    13→\usepackage{subcaption}
    14→
    15→% Theorem environments
    16→\newtheorem{theorem}{Theorem}[section]
    17→\newtheorem{lemma}[theorem]{Lemma}
    18→\newtheorem{proposition}[theorem]{Proposition}
    19→\newtheorem{corollary}[theorem]{Corollary}
    20→\theoremstyle{definition}
    21→\newtheorem{definition}[theorem]{Definition}
    22→\newtheorem{example}[theorem]{Example}
    23→\theoremstyle{remark}
    24→\newtheorem{remark}[theorem]{Remark}
    25→
    26→% Custom commands
    27→\newcommand{\R}{\mathbb{R}}
    28→\newcommand{\C}{\mathbb{C}}
    29→\newcommand{\N}{\mathbb{N}}
    30→\newcommand{\Z}{\mathbb{Z}}
    31→\newcommand{\T}{\mathcal{T}}
    32→\newcommand{\e}{\mathrm{e}}
    33→\DeclareMathOperator{\lcm}{lcm}
    34→\DeclareMathOperator{\esymm}{e}
    35→\DeclareMathOperator{\psymm}{p}
    36→
    37→\title{Rotated Roots of Unity and Chebyshev Polynomials:\\A Geometric Construction}
    38→
    39→\author{Eric Vergo}
    40→
    41→\date{\today}
    42→
    43→\begin{document}
    44→
    45→\maketitle
    46→
    47→\begin{abstract}
    48→We establish a surprising connection between the discrete geometry of roots of unity and the classical Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind.
    49→When the $N$-th roots of unity are rotated by an arbitrary angle $\varphi$ and projected onto the real axis, the resulting points serve as roots of a polynomial which, after appropriate scaling, differs from the $N$-th Chebyshev polynomial $T_N(x)$ only by a constant term that depends on $\varphi$.
    50→All other coefficients remain invariant under rotation.
    51→Our proof proceeds through discrete orthogonality relations for roots of unity, establishes power sum invariance via binomial expansion techniques, and applies Newton's identities to connect power sums with polynomial coefficients.
    52→This result provides a geometric interpretation of Chebyshev polynomials and reveals deep connections between discrete harmonic analysis, symmetric function theory, and orthogonal polynomial families.
    53→\end{abstract}
    54→
    55→\section{Introduction}
    56→
    57→The Chebyshev polynomials of the first kind, denoted $T_N(x)$, form one of the most important families of orthogonal polynomials, with applications spanning approximation theory, numerical analysis, and harmonic analysis~\cite{mason2002chebyshev, rivlin1990chebyshev}.
    58→These polynomials are typically defined either through the trigonometric identity
    59→\begin{equation}
    60→T_N(\cos\theta) = \cos(N\theta),
    61→\end{equation}
    62→or via the three-term recurrence relation
    63→\begin{equation}
    64→T_0(x) = 1, \quad T_1(x) = x, \quad T_{n+1}(x) = 2xT_n(x) - T_{n-1}(x).
    65→\end{equation}
    66→
    67→In this paper, we present a novel geometric construction of Chebyshev polynomials using rotated roots of unity. Consider the $N$-th roots of unity on the complex unit circle:
    68→\begin{equation}
    69→\omega_k = \e^{2\pi i k/N}, \quad k = 0, 1, \ldots, N-1.
    70→\end{equation}
    71→When these roots are rotated by an angle $\varphi$ (equivalently, multiplied by $\e^{i\varphi}$) and projected onto the real axis, we obtain the $N$ real numbers
    72→\begin{equation}\label{eq:rotated_roots}
    73→r_k(\varphi) = \cos\left(\varphi + \frac{2\pi k}{N}\right), \quad k = 0, 1, \ldots, N-1.
    74→\end{equation}
    75→
    76→\begin{figure}[t]
    77→\centering
    78→\includegraphics[width=\textwidth]{../paper_figures/paper_figure_N5_phi0.pdf}
    79→\caption{Geometric construction for $N=5$ at rotation angle $\varphi = 0$.
    80→Red points on the unit circle represent rotated roots of unity; pink points on the real axis are their projections $r_k(\varphi)$.
    81→The blue curve shows the scaled polynomial $S_N(x; \varphi)$ with these projections as roots.
    82→Generated using Manim Community Edition v0.19.0.}
    83→\label{fig:N5_construction}
    84→\end{figure}
    85→
    86→Let $P_N(x; \varphi)$ denote the monic polynomial having these projected values as roots:
    87→\begin{equation}\label{eq:monic_poly}
    88→P_N(x; \varphi) = \prod_{k=0}^{N-1} \left(x - \cos\left(\varphi + \frac{2\pi k}{N}\right)\right).
